# Scenario: MODEM UNRESPONSIVE — generic. Customer reports "we send AT commands
# and nothing comes back. Sometimes it works after a power-cycle, sometimes not."
# Key signals:
#   No response to "AT" repeated — empty replies.
#   First successful response only after several attempts (autobaud may be
#   adapting on a new cold-boot session).
#   No URCs of any kind (would expect +CGEV, +CREG, etc. on a healthy modem).
# Diagnosis: this is a PRE-NETWORK problem. The radio stack hasn't even gotten
# the chance to fail. Likely causes ranked by frequency:
#   1. INSUFFICIENT POWER — Cat-1 and LTE TX peaks can hit 2 A momentarily.
#      A 500 mA USB supply will brown out under TX load. Symptoms include:
#      modem boots OK, responds to AT for a while, then goes dark when it tries
#      to attach (because attach involves TX bursts).
#   2. UART WIRING — RX/TX swapped, UART level mismatch (3.3 V vs 1.8 V), or
#      missing ground reference. Some modules use 1.8 V UART and require a
#      level shifter to talk to a 3.3 V/5 V MCU.
#   3. BAUD RATE — modem is stuck at non-default baud. Try autobaud by sending
#      "AT\r" several times at common rates (115200, 9600, 460800).
#   4. RTS/CTS FLOW CONTROL — host has flow control enabled but modem disabled
#      (or vice versa); buffers fill, no data flows.
#   5. RESET / ENABLE PIN — modem is held in reset, or the PWRKEY pulse was
#      too short on power-up.
#   6. FIRMWARE DOWNLOAD MODE — modem booted into FOTA/DFU mode and won't
#      respond to normal AT until reflashed.
# Customer guidance:
#   - Measure VBAT under load with a scope. Look for >300 mV droops.
#   - Verify wiring: RX-TX-GND, RTS/CTS if used, level shift if module is 1.8 V.
#   - Try autobaud from a clean cold boot.
#   - Check ENABLE/PWRKEY pin sequence per module datasheet.
#   - If only ATI ever responds and nothing else, suspect bricked firmware.
# Triage tip: ALWAYS rule out hardware before chasing network-layer symptoms.
# Five minutes of multimeter work saves five hours of log analysis.

